00:09:19.150 --> 00:09:21.050
and also economics.

00:09:21.050 --> 00:09:27.030
Tells us in the climate of the past now.
We have the earth's orbit causing warming,

00:09:27.030 --> 00:09:32.830
making CO2 rise as the ocean warms and out
gases, CO2, and then causes further

00:09:32.830 --> 00:09:39.100
warming as an amplifier. So that's the
whole end of story about human caused

00:09:39.100 --> 00:09:45.350
climate change. Now I'm going to move on
into this idea that the first evidence for

00:09:45.350 --> 00:09:49.900
agriculture was seen during this abrupt
warming.

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:55.740
This is a fascinating topic and it's
mostly, I think, the work of Brian Baird

00:09:55.740 --> 00:10:00.070
who used to be here at UCSD. Who
discovered that the very first

00:10:00.070 --> 00:10:07.260
domesticated plants, I think they were
barley seeds, actually, occur within plus

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:12.020
or minus 200 years of this abrupt warming
event right here. Seen, this is actually

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:16.210
the Greenland temperature, but it's a lot
of the northern hemisphere European

00:10:16.210 --> 00:10:17.610
temperature as well.

00:10:17.610 --> 00:10:23.250
Then this is a methane record from the ice
core and it seems to be a proxy for

00:10:23.250 --> 00:10:28.380
wetness. There's a great deal of increase
in northern hemisphere low latitude

00:10:28.380 --> 00:10:33.130
rainfall at this time. This all happened
in about 30 years. These are very fast

00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:38.030
events. There's about half of the
temperature change seems to have occurred

00:10:38.030 --> 00:10:39.620
in one year.

00:10:39.620 --> 00:10:46.050
These are the kinds of things that could
impose very large stresses on humans

00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:52.750
potentially because there's not enough
time to adapt. What's amazing about this

00:10:52.750 --> 00:10:59.670
is that people seem to have completely
changed in a very short time their mode of

00:10:59.670 --> 00:11:03.750
existence from hunting and gathering to
farming right here.

00:11:03.750 --> 00:11:08.190
It's probably because everything got so
much warmer and wetter that it was just

00:11:08.190 --> 00:11:13.220
really lush. Think about the Garden of
Eden. That's probably sometime in here. We

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:22.620
don't know whether it was 8,000 years or
12,000 years, whatever. That was an

00:11:22.620 --> 00:11:27.020
example of abrupt climate change that
probably greatly benefited our ancestors.

00:11:27.020 --> 00:11:32.460
Of course when it's cooling, it's drying
as well and that would be a period of

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:37.360
intense stress. There were probably
population bottle-necks at the time and

00:11:37.360 --> 00:11:43.500
those may be very important for evolution.
Because if you kill off 97% of the humans

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:49.980
then you just leave 3%, those will have
characters that will then be able to

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:54.850
spread widely without having to exchange
with a large gene pool.

00:11:54.850 --> 00:12:01.490
So you can get very powerful evolutionary
change through this bottlenecks and what's

00:12:01.490 --> 00:12:07.170
remarkable about this abrupt events is
they happen again and again. It's not just

00:12:07.170 --> 00:12:12.280
one of them it's 25 of them in the last
100,000 years and probably something like

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:15.820
20 in the 100,000 years before that.

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:20.210
All told, our ancestors probably went
through at least 100 of these bottlenecks.

00:12:20.210 --> 00:12:25.980
So it's a repeated form of boom and bust
and William Calvin had a very nice book

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:31.800
about this kind of boom and bust
evolutionary pumping hypothesis.

00:12:31.800 --> 00:12:36.590
I'm going to switch now to talk about the
physical science understanding that we

00:12:36.590 --> 00:12:40.960
have about abrupt climate change. What
causes it in the first place and as I

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:45.400
hinted at the beginning it's something to
do with ocean circulation. Warm water at

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:50.430
the surface in the north Atlantic is
carried by currents to this place around

00:12:50.430 --> 00:12:53.380
Greenland where it becomes cold and dense
enough to sink.

00:12:53.380 --> 00:12:59.490
Then it travels southwards along the
bottom of the ocean and what these seems

00:12:59.490 --> 00:13:04.790
to do is that it actually displaces the
earth's thermal equator north of the

00:13:04.790 --> 00:13:08.530
geographic equator. The northern
hemisphere today is quite a bit warmer

00:13:08.530 --> 00:13:10.830
than the southern hemisphere.

00:13:10.830 --> 00:13:16.310
We believe that from theory and evidence
that this circulation is capable of

00:13:16.310 --> 00:13:21.340
shutting off. So that's what a cooling is
and when it turns back on that's what an

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:27.230
abrupt warming is. This is kind of what
the Paleo records look like of this

00:13:27.230 --> 00:13:32.620
phenomena of turning on and shutting off
the north Atlantic circulation.

00:13:32.620 --> 00:13:37.790
In the northern records you see abrupt
warmings at the times when the circulation

00:13:37.790 --> 00:13:44.360
goes on. In the southern hemisphere, this
is Antarctica, you actually see a gradual

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:51.190
warming during times when the north is
cold and then an inflection point towards

00:13:51.190 --> 00:13:58.760
gradual cooling in the south. This is very
strong evidence that this really is the

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:00.430
ocean circulation.

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:05.590
This is from a very recent ice core we
drilled that just finished and we got

00:14:05.590 --> 00:14:12.970
published in Nature a few weeks ago. This
is one of the main findings from this ice

00:14:12.970 --> 00:14:19.890
core is that because we can now date the
two hemispheres relative to each other to

00:14:19.890 --> 00:14:26.390
a precision of about 50 years. We can show
that the northern abrupt warming leads the

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:31.350
southern transition to cooling which is
shown here by about 200 years.

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:35.160
That's very interesting because that
really confirms that this is the ocean

00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:42.400
circulation that is doing this. I think
it's the latest in a long line of pieces

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:46.970
of evidence that support the notion that
it is this ocean circulation sort of

00:14:46.970 --> 00:14:50.540
oscillating and flipping on and off that
does this.

00:14:50.540 --> 00:14:54.890
Will it happen again in the near future?
Is an abrupt climate change something we

00:14:54.890 --> 00:15:01.090
have to worry about? Well you may have
seen the movie The Day After Tomorrow.

00:15:01.090 --> 00:15:05.850
It's something that is permeated into the
public consciousness but I think the

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:08.280
answer is probably not.

00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:13.960
The reason I say that is that the Atlantic
Ocean is getting saltier today. In the

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:18.120
last 50 years it's increased its salinity
dramatically. You can sort of see that in

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:24.330
this cartoon here. The Atlantic is all
yellow which is an increase in salinity.

00:15:24.330 --> 00:15:28.440
The Pacific has a lot of blue and that
means a sort of decrease in salinity.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:32.630
So what's going on right now is that the
Atlantic is getting saltier. The Pacific

00:15:32.630 --> 00:15:37.440
is getting fresher and that's exactly what
we expect to happen in a warming world

00:15:37.440 --> 00:15:43.980
because warm air holds more water vapor.
So it's impossible to transport more vapor

00:15:43.980 --> 00:15:49.210
out of the Atlantic into the Pacific
across Panama as you see here.

00:15:49.210 --> 00:15:53.450
Basically whenever the world gets warmer
the Atlantic gets saltier. The salt

00:15:53.450 --> 00:15:57.970
actually densifies the water, makes it
easy to sink and it actually protects that

00:15:57.970 --> 00:16:04.290
circulation. While there was some worry
maybe 15 years ago that the Atlantic

00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:08.970
circulation would shut down due to global
warming. I think we can say now we've

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:15.680
learned something, science moves on. It is
now very unlikely this will happen again.

00:16:15.680 --> 00:16:22.410
The other thing of course is that we don't
have the amplifying factor of sea ice. Sea

00:16:22.410 --> 00:16:29.310
ice makes the ocean turn from dark to
white. So it greatly exacerbates the

00:16:29.310 --> 00:16:33.980
effects of the overturning circulation
shutting off.

00:16:33.980 --> 00:16:40.790
My take home messages. I hope I have
convinced you that abrupt climate change

00:16:40.790 --> 00:16:47.950
did stimulate farming and there's a very
very interesting story that's only just

00:16:47.950 --> 00:16:53.080
beginning to be understood. It's very
probable that many many abrupt climate

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:58.840
changes prior to this one that stimulated
farming, played a role by creating

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:08.000
bottlenecks that made the survivors of
this event able to radiate out into an

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.190
empty niche after the event.

00:17:11.190 --> 00:17:17.710
Very probably I think, also, encouraged
people who could do things differently

00:17:17.710 --> 00:17:23.440
than their parents were doing them. As I
have some kids who are becoming teenagers

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:27.450
I know a lot about this sort of
oppositional, don't do what your parents

00:17:27.450 --> 00:17:33.500
were doing kind of stuff and I just wonder
if maybe the teenager kind of thing has

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:38.980
its origins in abrupt climate change.

00:17:38.980 --> 00:17:44.300
Because if your parents are telling you to
eat fruit and the climate just crashed and

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:48.630
you say I do things differently than my
parents. I'm going to eat roots instead of

00:17:48.630 --> 00:17:53.030
fruits. Well you might be the one who
actually survives because you're a root

00:17:53.030 --> 00:17:58.030
eater. I'm just wondering maybe this
population bottlenecks somehow encouraged

00:17:58.030 --> 00:18:03.370
sort of contrarian thinking.

00:18:03.370 --> 00:18:08.360
Atlantic Ocean overturning circulation is
the culprit, I think. We can now say that

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:13.810
causes abrupt climate change. Will it
happen? Again in the future probably not.

00:18:13.810 --> 00:18:17.650
That's one thing we can breathe easier
about. Check that one off the list. More

00:18:17.650 --> 00:18:22.040
salt less sea ice in our future. Thank
you.

